1. Introduction

The AI job market has grown rapidly in recent years, driven by advances in machine learning, generative AI and automation technologies. This project analyzes AI-related job postings from 2022 to 2024 using a refined Kaggle dataset enhanced with additional skill and education indicators.

Key focus areas include identifying popular job titles, analyzing geographic and sector distributions, examining experience and education requirements and exploring demand for specific AI skills. These insights aim to help job seekers, educators and professionals understand current trends and skill demands in this fast-evolving field.


2. Dataset and Metodology

This analysis uses a modified version of the Kaggle AI Job Listings Dataset, with added columns marking specific skills extracted from job descriptions. For analytical purposes, the various job titles have been grouped into specific categories to facilitate clearer insights. These categories include:

  • Generalist ML Engineers

  • ML Engineer Software

  • ML Engineer NLP, Generative AI, Deep Learning

  • ML Engineer Ops (including Cloud & Big Data)

  • ML Engineer Research (including Robotics)

  • ML Engineer / Data Scientist

This grouping allows for focused analysis of skills, education requirements and trends within each distinct AI job function.

The dataset covers job titles, locations, experience levels, education, skills and posting dates from 2022 through 2024.


3. Job Category Ranking

This section presents the distribution of job postings across predefined machine learning (ML) engineer categories. Rather than listing individual job titles, roles are grouped into broader categories such as Generalist, ML Engineer Software, NLP/Generative AI/Deep Learning and more. The goal is to provide a clearer picture of the AI job market’s structure.


df %>%
  count(edited_category, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(edited_category, n), y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = " Job Category Ranking", x = "Job Title", y = "Count")

The graph clearly shows that ML Engineer Generalist roles are the most predominant by a significant margin, followed distantly by ML Engineer Software positions. This suggests that most job listings do not specify a particular type of machine learning engineering, but rather seek professionals with broad, generalist skill sets. At the other end of the spectrum, the hybrid ML Engineer / Data Scientist category appears the least represented. However, it’s important to note that this dataset focuses specifically on ML Engineer roles. Pure Data Scientist positions were not included, and are likely in higher demand than what is reflected here.


4. Geographic Distribution

Geography plays a critical role in AI job availability. This section explores where these roles are concentrated across the U.S., highlighting the most active locations for ML hiring.


4.1 Top 10 States

Here, we identify the ten U.S. states with the highest number of AI-related job postings. This helps illustrate regional trends and states that serve as major hubs for AI talent.


df %>%
  filter(!is.na(state), state != "N/A") %>%
  count(state, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(state, n), y = n)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "#EFC000FF") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 10 States by Number of Job Postings", x = "State", y = "Number of Postings")

California clearly dominates AI job postings, underscoring its position as the primary tech hub in the US. New York holds second place, while Texas ranks third and is rapidly expanding its tech scene, particularly in cities like Austin. Washington comes in fourth, supported by major tech employers such as Microsoft and Amazon.

This section dives deeper into the urban distribution of AI jobs, listing the top ten cities where ML job postings are most prevalent. These insights are useful for those considering relocation for career opportunities.


df %>%

San Francisco and New York clearly lead the AI job market, reflecting their status as major tech and business hubs. Notably, there is a strong predominance of Californian cities in the list, including Mountain View, Palo Alto, San Jose, Sunnyvale, and the San Francisco Bay Area, highlighting Silicon Valley’s continued importance as a major tech hub. Other cities like Seattle, Irving, and Austin also appear, reflecting growing tech activity beyond California and the East Coast.


5. Job Postings by Sector

AI roles are in demand across various industries. This section breaks down job postings by sector (e.g., Tech, Finance, Recruiting) to show where AI talent is most sought after.


df %>%
  filter(!is.na(sector)) %>%
  count(sector, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(sector, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "#66c2a5") +

  labs(
    title = "Top 10 Sectors for AI/ML Job Listings",
    x = "Sector",
    y = "Number of Postings"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12)

The distribution of AI job postings by sector shows a strong focus on software development, followed by IT services and consulting, and technology, information and internet industries. Interestingly, nonprofit organizations and primary and secondary education also feature prominently, indicating AI’s expanding role beyond traditional tech sectors. Staffing and recruiting ranks notably high, reflecting the active search for AI talent. While defense and space manufacturing sectors appear in the top 10, their share remains relatively small until 2024, highlighting a modest but ongoing investment in AI technologies.


6. Experience Level Distribution

Understanding what level of experience employers are seeking can help job seekers position themselves better. This section analyzes the distribution of postings across different experience levels, from entry-level to senior roles.


df %>%
  count(edited_experience_level) %>%

  geom_col() +

  theme_minimal()


The bar chart shows that mid-level experience is the most in demand, followed by senior, founder, and lead positions. It’s important to note that for job listings without a specified experience level, mid-level has been assigned by default.


7. Evolution Over Time

This section explores how AI job postings have evolved over time. By examining monthly trends we can identify hiring cycles, peak periods, and potential market shifts in AI demand.


df %>%
  group_by(published_year, published_month, edited_category) %>%
  summarise(postings = n()) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(date = as.Date(paste(published_year, published_month, "01", sep = "-"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = postings, color = edited_category)) +
  geom_line(size = 1) +
  labs(title = "Evolution of Job Postings by Category Over Time",
       x = "Date",
       y = "Number of Postings",
       color = "Job Category") +
  theme_minimal()

The graph shows relatively low activity until mid-2023, with a notable increase beginning in December 2023. Job postings have been steadily rising throughout 2024, culminating in an significant peak in May/June 2024. This sudden growth is unlikely due to seasonality, as similar peaks were not observed in previous years. Here are a few possible explainations:

  • A renewed industry push for AI talent, possibly driven by recent technological advancements and increased market demand.

  • Major events in the AI space such as product launches (e.g., GPT-4o), regulatory developments, or large-scale investment announcements.

  • However, given the magnitude of the spike, jumping from under 100 to around 400 postings in a short period, it is most likely due to the dataset’s collection method. A temporary increase in scraping activity or a change in coverage may have caused an unusually high number of listings to be captured during that month.

The overall pattern appears consistent across most job categories.


8. Education Requirements


This section summarizes which educational backgrounds are most commonly required for AI roles. The focus is on core disciplines like computer science, software engineering, electrical engineering and statistics.


8.1 Generalist ML Engineers


We analyze education trends for Generalist ML Engineer roles, highlighting which qualifications are most often required in these versatile positions.


library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(stringr)
library(DT)

education_generalist <- df %>%
  filter(str_detect(edited_category, "Generalist")) %>%
  select(
    edited_education_computer_science,
    edited_education_software_engineering,
    edited_education_electrical_engineering,
    edited_education_other_engineering,
    edited_education_statistics,
    edited_education_mathematics,
    edited_education_physics,
    edited_education_unspecified
  ) %>%
  rename(
    `Computer Science` = edited_education_computer_science,
    `Software Engineering` = edited_education_software_engineering,
    `Electrical Engineering` = edited_education_electrical_engineering,
    `Core Engineering` = edited_education_other_engineering,
    `Statistics` = edited_education_statistics,
    `Mathematics` = edited_education_mathematics,
    `Physics` = edited_education_physics,
    `Unspecified` = edited_education_unspecified
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "Education",
    values_to = "Required"
  ) %>%
  filter(Required == TRUE) %>%
  count(Education, name = "Count") %>%
  arrange(desc(Count)) %>%
  mutate(
    Percent = paste0(round(Count / sum(Count) * 100), "%")
  ) %>%
  select(Education, Percent)

datatable_obj <- DT::datatable(
  education_generalist,
  options = list(
    pageLength = 15,
    scrollX = TRUE,
    headerCallback = JS(
      "function(thead, data, start, end, display){",
      "  $(thead).find('th').eq(1).css('text-align', 'right');",
      "}"
    )
  ),
  rownames = FALSE
) %>%
  DT::formatStyle(
    'Percent',
    'text-align' = 'right'
  )

datatable_obj


Generalist ML Engineers primarily come from Computer Science (27%) and Core Engineering (27%), showing a strong preference for technical and engineering backgrounds. Software Engineering (16%) and Statistics (15%) follow, emphasizing programming and data skills. Fewer come from Mathematics (6%), Physics (4%), and Electrical Engineering (2%), while 2% have unspecified education, indicating a small portion with nontraditional or unclear paths.

11. Job Postings by Skill Profile (PCA)


To conclude, this section uses dimensionality reduction techniques to visually group job postings based on their full skill profiles. It reveals patterns in how skill sets cluster across roles, helping us understand specialization within the AI job market.


library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyr)

# 1. Select skill-related columns and group
skills_df <- df %>%
  select(contains("_coding_"), contains("_category_"), contains("_tools_"))

# 2. Optional: give readable column names
colnames(skills_df) <- gsub("edited_skills_", "", colnames(skills_df))

# 3. Convert logicals to numeric (TRUE = 1, FALSE = 0)
skills_numeric <- skills_df %>% mutate(across(everything(), as.integer))

# 4. Run PCA on job posts by skill profile
pca_result <- prcomp(skills_numeric, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

# 5. Take first 2 principal components for plotting
pca_df <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x[, 1:2])
pca_df$category <- df$edited_category  # Add job role label

# 6. Scatter plot
ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = category)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Job Postings by Skill Profile (PCA)",
       x = "Principal Component 1",
       y = "Principal Component 2") +
  theme_minimal()


This PCA plot groups AI/ML job listings by skill profiles, reducing high-dimensional data into two components. It shows that most roles—especially generalist and data scientist positions—overlap significantly, while more specialized categories like NLP or research roles are more distinct, suggesting tighter clustering of skill sets in those areas.


12. Conclusion


This analysis reveals clear trends in the AI job market between 2022 and 2024. Generalist ML Engineer roles remain the most sought-after, while specialization in* NLP, Generative AI and cloud operations is growing rapidly. California, particularly the Bay Area, continues to lead in job volume, though other states like Texas and Washington are rising. Mid-level roles dominate, with strong demand for core programming skills (especially Python), cloud tools (AWS, TensorFlow), and data frameworks (SQL, Spark).

The data also shows a consistent preference for technical degrees such as Computer Science and Core Engineering, with varying emphasis depending on the job type. Emerging AI technologies are clearly shaping hiring patterns, pointing to a future where adaptability and continuous learning are essential.

As AI evolves, this dataset and methodology can be updated to track ongoing changes in roles, skills and locations. Future work might include global job postings, salary analysis or integration with LinkedIn data.
